      "e menor que k, para\nqualquer k natural.  Pelo lado direito temos que âŒˆlog(n-1)âŒ‰ <= k <=>\nn-1 <= 2^k.  Pelo lado esquerdo:\n\n    âŒˆlog(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1)âŒ‰ + 1 <= k <=> âŒˆlog(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1)âŒ‰ <= k-1,\n                                 <=> log(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1) <= k-1,\n                                 <=> âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1 <= 2^(k-1),\n                                 <=> âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ <= 2^(k-1) + 1,\n                                 <=> (n+1)/2 <= 2^(k-1) + 1,\n                                 <=> n+1 <= 2^k + 2,\n                                 <=> n-1 <= 2^k.\n\nO que completa a prova, uma vez que ambos os lados chegam na mesma\nproposiأ§أ£o.\n\n-/\n\n\n/- 4.4 : see the book -/\n\n/-!\n# Exercicio 4.5\n\nIndexing the coordinates from zero, the positions are\n(0, 9), (5, 6), (7, 5), (9, 0)\n-/\n\n-- # Exercicio 4.6\n\n-- #eval D2.searchâ‚پ (خ» (x, y) => x ^ 3 + y ^ 3) 1729\n\n\n-- # Exercicio 4.7\n\nnamespace BST1\n\ndef flatcat : (t : Tree a) â†’ (xs: List a) â†’ List a\n| .null, xs => xs\n| .node l x r, xs => flatcat l (x :: flatcat r xs)\n\ndef Tree.flattenâ‚پ (t : Tree a) : List a :=\n flatcat t []\n\ntheorem flatten_eq_helper_accum (t : Tree a) (xs: List a)\n  : t.flatten ++ xs = flatcat t xs := by\n  induction t generalizing xs with\n  | null => rfl\n  | node l x r ihl ihr =>\n    rw [flatcat, â†گihr]\n    rw [â†گihl (x :: (r.flatten ++ xs))]\n    rw [List.append_cons]\n    rw [â†گ List.append_assoc]\n    rw [Tree.flatten]\n\nexample (t: Tree a) : t.flatten = t.flattenâ‚پ := by\n  induction t with\n  | null => exact rfl\n  | node l x r ihl ihr =>\n    rw [Tree.flattenâ‚پ]\n    simp [â†گ flatten_eq_helper_accum]\n\nend BST1\n\n-- # Exercicio 4.8\n\n\nnamespace BST1\n\nexample {خ± : Type} (t : Tree خ±) :\n  t.height â‰¤ t.size âˆ§ t.size < 2 ^ t.height := by\n  apply And.intro\n  {\n   induction t with\n   | null  => simp [Tree.height, Tree.size]\n   | node tâ‚پ x tâ‚‚ ihl ihr =>\n     simp [Tree.height, Tree.size]\n     sorry\n  }\n  {\n  induction t with\n  | null => simp [Tree.height, Tree.size]\n  | node tâ‚پ x tâ‚‚ ihl ihr =>\n    simp [Tree.height, Tree.size]\n    sorry\n```\n\nThe theorem is `t.height â‰¤ t.size âˆ§ t.size < 2 ^ t.height`.\n\nFor the first part, `t.height â‰¤ t.size`:\n- Base case: `t = null`. `0 â‰¤ 0` is true.\n- Inductive step: `t = node tâ‚پ x tâ‚‚`. `1 + max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height â‰¤ 1 + tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size`. This simplifies to `max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height â‰¤ tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size`. This is true because `tâ‚پ.height â‰¤ tâ‚پ.size` and `tâ‚‚.height â‰¤ tâ‚‚.size`, so `max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height â‰¤ tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size`.\n\nFor the second part, `t.size < 2 ^ t.height`:\n- Base case: `t = null`. `0 < 2 ^ 0 = 1` is true.\n- Inductive step: `t = node tâ‚پ x tâ‚‚`. `1 + tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size < 2 ^ (1 + max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height)`.\n  This simplifies to `1 + tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size < 2 * 2 ^ max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height`.\n  We need to show `1 + tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size < 2 * 2 ^ max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height`.\n\nLet's consider two cases:\n1. `tâ‚پ.height â‰¤ tâ‚‚.height`. Then `max tâ‚پ.height tâ‚‚.height = tâ‚‚.height`.\n   We need to show `1 + tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size < 2 * 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height`.\n   We have `tâ‚پ.size < 2 ^ tâ‚پ.height` and `tâ‚‚.size < 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height`.\n   Also `tâ‚پ.height â‰¤ tâ‚‚.height`.\n   So `tâ‚پ.size < 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height`.\n   `1 + tâ‚پ.size + tâ‚‚.size < 1 + 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height + 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height = 1 + 2 * 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height`.\n   We need to show `1 + 2 * 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height < 2 * 2 ^ tâ‚‚.height`.\n   This is equivalent to `1 < 0`, which is false.\n\nWait, this is the same problem as before. So the theorem is false.\n\nBut the theorem is given in the problem, so it must be true. So there must be something wrong with our understanding.\n\nWait, perhaps the theorem is `t.height â‰¤ t.size âˆ§ t.size â‰¤ 2 ^ t.height`.\n\nLet's check this:\n- For a single node: `0 â‰¤ 1` and `1 â‰¤ 1`. True.\n- For a tree with two nodes: `1 â‰¤ 2` and `2 â‰¤ 2`. True.\n\nSo the theorem should be `t.height â‰¤ t.size âˆ§ t.size â‰¤ 2 ^ t.height`.\n\nThe problem statement has `t.size < 2 ^ t.height`. So this is the theorem we have to prove, even if it's false for some cases.\n\nWait, so in Lean, we have to prove it, even if it's false. But Lean will detect the contradiction.\n\nWait, let's try to prove it in Lean.\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter4\nimport Fad.Chapter3\n\nnamespace Chapter4\n\n/- 4.2\nWe have smallest (a,b) = x such that f x < t â‰¤ f (x + 1)\nBut for t = 1024 and f x = x^2 below f x = t and f (x + 1) > t\n\n#eval D1.smallest (fun x => dbg_trace \"fun {x}\"; x * x) 1024 (0, 1024)\n#eval (fun x => dbg_trace \"fun {x}\"; x * x) 32\n#eval (fun x => dbg_trace \"fun {x}\"; x * x) 33\n-/\n\n/- 4.3\n\nVamos provar por induأ§أ£o que\n\nT(x) = âŒˆlog(n-1)âŒ‰.\n\nPara o caso base (n=2)\n\nT(2) = âŒˆlog(2-1)âŒ‰ = âŒˆlog(1)âŒ‰ = âŒˆ0âŒ‰ = 0.\n\nSupondo valido para k < n, vamos provar para n. Como âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ < n,\nvale a hipotese de inducao, entao temos que provar que:\n\nT(n) = âŒˆlog(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1)âŒ‰ + 1 = âŒˆlog(n-1)âŒ‰.\n\nPodemos mostrar por desigualdade indireta, mostrando que o lado\nesquerdo e menor que k se e somente o lado direito e menor que k, para\nqualquer k natural.  Pelo lado direito temos que âŒˆlog(n-1)âŒ‰ <= k <=>\nn-1 <= 2^k.  Pelo lado esquerdo:\n\n    âŒˆlog(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1)âŒ‰ + 1 <= k <=> âŒˆlog(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1)âŒ‰ <= k-1,\n                                 <=> log(âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1) <= k-1,\n                                 <=> âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ -1 <= 2^(k-1),\n                                 <=> âŒˆ(n+1)/2âŒ‰ <= 2^(k-1) + 1,\n                                 <=> (n+1)/2 <= 2^(k-1) + 1,\n                                 <=> n+1 <= 2^k + 2,\n                                 <=> n-1 <= 2^k.\n\nO que completa a prova, uma vez que ambos os lados chegam na mesma\nproposiأ§أ£o.\n\n-/\n\n\n/- 4.4 : see the book -/\n\n/-!\n# Exercicio 4.5\n\nIndexing the coordinates from zero, the positions are\n(0, 9), (5, 6), (7, 5), (9, 0